The paper focuses on formal models and fundamental limitations of performance for distributed decision-making in robotic networks, which is a topic that falls under the scope of multi-agent systems and distributed computing. Therefore, cs.MA (Multiagent Systems) and cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of I/O automata, which is a formalism commonly used in the study of distributed systems, and presents bounds on time, message, and byte complexity, which are relevant to the study of control systems (cs.SY) and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper sheds light on the relation between the tools developed by the Computer Science and Controls communities, which is a topic that falls under the scope of machine learning (cs.LG).
